snippet.textDisplay:
I developed symptoms in late February/early March but I wasn't tested because at the time, testing kits weren't readily available. Despite travel to a hotspot, having a negative influenza test, and having the symptoms, the department of health wouldn't authorize a test because I couldn't positively identify anyone that may have been a carrier. My doctor ended up classifying it as an unknown virus so I'm essentially left with the possibility that I may have had it but no way to know.


So I ended up being really sick for about 5 days and then gradually feeling better with some unknown virus...and who knows if I passed it on to anyone else! I genuinely feel let down by the health system in the US.

snippet.textDisplay: I'm currently in the military stationed in San Diego, CA. Even though there has been 250+ confirmed cases in our county, our base is still up and running. On the other hand, there are still hundreds of people allowed to go in to the commissary and the exchange. Our unit still meets for work every day and we have formations of 30+ people every day. snippet.textDisplay:
Maybe some medical professionals could back me up on this or tell me where I'm wrong.

Having a healthy immune system is not quote the same as being physically fit. The go hand in hand, to a point, but are different concepts.

For example, I don't have a six pack. I don't fit in a models clothes. I'm over 40 and have a few more pounds than I can count on my fingers. But. .. I can run 2 miles in 19 minutes. I don't have chiseled abs, but I can lift 180% of my body weight. I literally move tons of weight every day with nothing but muscle power. Sleep deprivation and temperature extremes are more common than showers and meals. In one work day I am exposed to temperatures ranging from -25°C to +30°C. And I work in these environments for 15 hours straight. 5-6 days a week. After work I don't go home. I use public bathrooms 95% of the time, and I shower in public showers when I can. On average, every other day. I also occasionally deal with bio hazardous waste. Especially in flu season. When it is cold and rainy, I am frequently drenched in ice. I do this 340 days per Year and have been doing this for 16 years. I have been sick once. And it was Pneumonia. Because I worked through the Flu for 2 months prior. I haven't been sick since.

Some of it might be DNA. But I tend to believe it has more to do with the fact my body is constantly being exposed to harsh conditions and invasive threats. Every day. Yesterday I stood in howling -5°C wind in a T shirt and thin work slacks for three hours while pushing 1,200 kg. pallets 100 meters uphill. I don't use disinfectant. I used soap. Not teneside soap. Old fashioned hydroxide bar soap that I actually make myself. It has a 3% superfat. That is very little. It scours my skin dry, but I have always had oily skin, so the sebum is replaced right away naturally. That is genetic. I eat healthy. Lots of vegetables, and a good amount of lean meat. Not processed meat products, but actual meat. I consume exclusively simple carbohydrates from natural sources such as rice, oats, potatoes, and whole wheat flour. I drink plain tap water, without a high tech filter. First thing in the morning it tastes like rust. So what. I like it.

The point I am getting at is that I don't put my body in a glass case under a protected atmosphere and disinfect it 3 times daily. My immune system is very healthy. I just got back from a tour to Hamburg Germany 5 hours ago. I do three tours a week. CoViD19 is raging through this country. I doubt I am immune, but you never know. I know that if this virus wants my lungs, it's going to have to earn them with a blood stripe. Maybe I'll get it. Maybe I won't.

However ultimately only herd immunity will save humanity. Either through vaccination or immunity paid for in caskets like the black plague. I firmly believe many people have made themselves easy targets for many diseases by living too sterile and too comfortable while feeding themselves garbage with shit sauce. I know 19 year old kids who see a snow flake on TV and catch a cold. I know a 79 year old man who does the same job I do, just as well, and just as fast. He also survived 17 years in prison. He's tough. That's why he can still do it.

Long story short, I feel there is not enough being said about building natural resistance through physical robustness and work. I feel people in general have become weaker as life has become easier and more convenient. I am not promoting this as a recommendation of how to live. I am merely stating my opinion based on what I see and experience. Maybe there are some medical professionals reading this that could elaborate or critique. I'm not too old to learn. And I'm not young enough to know everything.

In any case, whether your immune system is a gladiator or blob fish, stay safe and healthy. Without your health, you truly have nothing. Protect it. And if you believe in any religion then may you be blessed by your God(s) and Godess (es). Humans will survive. That is not in question. Here is to hoping as many do as possible. Good luck and thank you for taking the time to read this.
